values:
des fois je me demande pourquoi je ne sauvegarde pas toutes ces entrées dans un fichier texte pour fermer ce journal. je n'y viens plus, c'est clair. et d'autre fois, je trouve ça bien de pouvoir accéder à ces parties de moi, à partir de n'importe où...

ok. je ne fermerai pas. mais je ne tenterai pas non plus de me motiver à updater plus souvent...

blergh...

j'adore 30 rock.

point is made.

going back to doing anything else than updating.

c cool... on est revenu au bon vieux temps où, quand un coloc revient d'une soirée en ayant manqué le match, il n'a même pas besoin de demander qui a gagné.

le canadien de la belle époque...

boarf. c'est pas parce que je n'écris pas deux jours que je n'écris plus...

mais bon... je crois que je vais me partir un blog. au lieu d'un journal.

suis retombé en enfance, ce week-end. j'ai téléchargé avant la fin de semaine un émulateur de nintendo et de super nes et à peu près tous les jeux possibles et inimaginables qui ont été faits pour les deux consoles de leur création à leur désuétude (hum, désolé pour le style lourdingue de cette phrase)

j'ai pas joué tant que ça, pressé que j'étais de retrouver mes classiques personnels et de faire le tri dans ce que je veux garder et ce dont je me fous. ya quand même presque 2000 jeux en tout.

les graphiques sont parfois surprenants. d'autres fois carrément ridicules. mais bon. ça m'a rappelé de bons souvenirs, les dodge ball et autres nhl 93...

sinon week-end cool, deux soirées occupées, vendredi au théâtre et samedi anniversaire d'un ami.

et là je me tâte... quoi faire d'abord ?

bof... un petit round de punck out, maybe...

je crois que c'est une espèce de misanthropie qui se développe. quand je reste trop longtemps seul, quand je n'ai pas "besoin" de sortir... je reste à l'intérieur, parce que l'extérieur, c'est trop forçant.. il faut que je prenne ma douche, que je prépare mes affaires.

et c'est malsain.

donc, première étape : recommencer à m'entraîner. doucement, au départ. de la marche rapide. pour, oui, économiser, et aussi parce que mon corps n'acceptera pas de recommencer rapidement comme j'ai déjà pu le faire.

en l'écrivant ici, je scelle une sorte de pacte. avec moi-même.

dès lundi - pourquoi faire aujourd'hui ce que je peux remettre à l'undi - je marche une heure par jour. de 7 à 8 le matin, mettons.

deuxième étape: sortir de chez moi pour travailler. séparer lieux de détente et de travail.

troisième étape... euh... je verrai...

je vais commencer par deux étapes..

depuis quelques semaines, je me suis rendu compte que, même sans le savoir avant, j'étais depuis super longtemps un fan d'ennio morricone. je connaissais ses musiques, sans savoir qu'elles étaient de lui.

shame on me, wannabe cinéaste. enfin.

et là je me tape sa discographie complète. majestueusement grandiose. et on ne peut pas renier le fait que ça aide à écrire en maudit.

je lisais récemment un auteur, péju, je crois, qui disait qu'écrivain, ce n'est pas un titre, mais un état. je ne peux qu'être d'accord avec lui. tout nous inspire, n'importe quand.

le problème, c'est que j'ai perdu la bonne habitude de traîner des carnets de note. on dirait que depuis que je suis cloîtré chez moi, travailleur autonome et misanthrope obligé (mais obligeant aussi, j'imagine) que je suis, la vie a pris un autre tournant. comme si le nombre d'heures dans une journée était fixe : pas assez. je me lève tard. je perds du temps. 

je dois me trouver un bureau. juste pour sortir physiquement de chez moi. séparer le monde du travail de la maison. encore faut-il que je le paye, ce bureau. et là, ça ne me semble pas gagné d'avance.

enfin bon.

une fois, j'ai commencé un roman. je ne l'ai pas fini. 
une autre fois, j'ai voulu faire de la musique. je n'ai pas continué.

je suis de la génération lelouesque, celle qui ne peut s'intéresser plus que 2 minutes à quoi que ce soit.

comme ce journal.

depuis que je suis à montréal, installé dans mes pénates, quasi confortable, ma vie a pris un drôle de tournant. l'écriture pour le plaisir n'existe plus. comme si je n'avais plus rien à raconter d'assez potable, pour le hurler dans les yeux du lecteur qui passe.

je bosse. point à la ligne.
c'est morne.
c'est l'automne.

l'automne amène toujours cette pulsion de mort chez moi. je ne parle pas d'idées suicidaires, non, mais juste ce sentiment d'être collé aux saisons. 

c'est morne dehors ; c'est morne en-dedans, quoi.

j'a recommencé à écrire un roman. pour encore une fois le mettre sur la glace. j'étais motivé à faire de la musique. les portes ne s'ouvrent pas.

devrais-je partir ou bien rester, comme disait l'autre.

le pauvre leloup, qui, justement, a vraiment pété un câble. là où le génie se manifestait, la folie commence à prendre la place.

mince consolation : je ne suis pas un génie.

Since the beginning of time, and more specifically ever since last Valentine's Day, people have been spilling romantic beans. What follows, today and Wednesday, is a chronological account -- in the language of this year's overheard quotes -- of love.

GETTING ACQUAINTED

"Telling a woman she would make a fortune as a hooker is not a compliment!'' (One man to another, at the Balboa Cafe, overheard by Tim Norton.)

"Are you involved with someone?'' "Usually.'' (Man to man and vice versa, overheard on Market Street by Marsha Seeley.)

"It means one of two things. Either he likes you, or he's looking for a booty call.'' (Young woman on cell phone entering Gaia Building in Berkeley, overheard by Hannah Karpilow.)

"Wait. Are you dominant or am I?'' (Young woman to young man, overheard on Broadway by Marta Johansen.)

"Did you know it's a mitzvah to have sex while sitting Shiva?'' (One bicyclist to another, both in full regalia, overheard in Venice, Calif., by Flicka McGurrin and Dottie Leroux.)

"Hey, I'm down with Moses, too.'' (Man approaching a woman, overheard at La Bodeguita del Medio in Palo Alto by Bill Bucy.)

"I'm an Open Source kind of girl.'' (Young woman at Ramada Inn on Market Street, overheard by Rick Kleffel.)

PICKY, PICKY, PICKY

"Women in San Francisco have a natural hostility.'' "You have to go to the East Bay, to Walnut Creek, Emeryville.'' (San Francisco cop to San Francisco cop, overheard on Potrero Hill by Lisa Geduldig.)

"He's a dork. He needs to man up.'' (Teenage girl on cell phone, overheard on a Van Ness bus by Margarita Landazuri.)

"I don't care if someone has M.D. after their name. OK, so she's a neurosurgeon. But is she hot?'' (Man to his parents, overheard at AT&T Park by The Chronicle's Heather Knight.)

"She's really into androgynous guys. No, like post-op transsexuals.'' (Man on cell phone, overheard leaving the N Judah by Ben Vance.)

"Does he have all his own teeth?'' (One middle-aged woman to another, overheard on the Muni Metro by Brian McDermott.)

"I wouldn't let my daughter go out with any man who said he doesn't like his mother.'' (Man to man, overheard outside the Coffee Roastery in San Anselmo by Jim Mitchell.)

"I don't do guts. I don't do bald. I don't do geezers. Three non-negotiables in my dating equation.'' (Woman to woman, overheard in front of San Francisco Center by Catherine Luciano.)

"Ain't nothin' sexy 'bout pigeon-toed men.'' (Overheard at Daddy's Bar on Castro Street by Kevin Dunn.)

"I've had enough hippie guys. I need more superficial, materialistic guys.'' (Forty-ish woman to another, overheard at Tabla Cafe in Larkspur by Larken Bradley.)

UNCLEAR ON A PARTICULAR CONCEPT

"Oh, no, girlfriend, it's not like Cincinnati. Out here you have to question everybody's sexuality.'' (Young woman on cell phone near Pier 39, overheard by D. Robert Foster.)

"I swear if he wasn't dating me, I'd think he was gay!'' (Woman on cell phone, overheard boarding bus at Stonestown by Julie Pilossoph.)

"Lemme tell you something: If her name were Victor and she were a boy, I might be more interested.'' (Young man on cell phone, overheard on Sutter Street by Nancy Blair.)

KNOW THYSELF

"For the last week I've been a raging wall of manliness.'' (One teen-age boy discussing his girlfriend with two companions, overheard on the 24-Divisadero line by Paul Tominac.)

"My mechanism of passion is just so frigging complex.'' (Man to man, overheard at a cafe in Los Angeles by Anne Buelteman.)

"I'm too young to be his mother and I'm too old to steal his boyfriend.'' (Clerk at Mother Trucker's grocery store near Nevada City, overheard by Craig Sebastian.)

"I don't know why my husband thinks a younger woman would want him. I don't want him and we're the same age.'' (Woman to woman, overheard on the Bridgeway in Sausalito by Joe Mac.)

"That would be your Godzilla to my Bambi.'' (Young man on cell phone, overheard on Shattuck Avenue in Berkeley by Margaret Kendall.)

"She was a hard-core Catholic and I'm the anti-Christ. It was the ruin of my first marriage.'' (Old salt sitting at picnic table, overhead outside the Marina Green snack stand by Margo Freistadt.)

"It's so weird. I used to be irresistible. I don't know what happened.'' (One young woman to another, overheard at 16th and Guerrero by Mark Fulmer.)

"It's obvious that I really like you, but all my friends think my taste in men is abhorrent.'' (Woman to man, ascending steps in a Marina apartment building, overheard by Mike Rogen.)

GO FOR IT

"It's OK sweetie, a lot of good relationships are built on booze.'' (One young woman to another, overheard in Walnut Creek by Erin Day.)

"I want to download you.'' (Middle-aged man to young blond woman, overheard in a downtown restaurant by J.J., who thinks the subject was business.)

"Will you slam dunk my heart?'' (Gent to 6'1''-tall Jessica Johnson, overheard on Fremont Street by Frances Browne.)

"Even though they were Republicans, they were really in love.'' (Man describing Nancy and Ronald Reagan, overheard at Aumakua in San Francisco by Jo Ann Shain.)

"Look, we could buy our first sculpture together.'' (Young woman to man, walking arm in arm in Sausalito, overheard by J.K. Slate.)

"O.K., I'll pretend we're getting married if you really think it will help.'' (Male college student to female on UC Berkeley campus, overheard by Linnea Nasman.)

"I don't remember anything I said in the cab last night, but I'm sure it was all pretty stupid.'' "You said that you loved me.'' (Young man and young woman converse, overheard on Clement Street by Donna Laemmlen.)

"He said he really likes me and could fall in love with me, you know, blah blah blah.'' (Man to man at 24-Hour Fitness on Market Street, overheard by The Chronicle's Heather Knight.)

YES AND NO

"I just had a baby! I'm too tired to plan a wedding!'' (Overheard in a Marin County beauty salon by Lindy King.)

"Did you mean to forbid all the fun in my life by marrying me?'' (Woman eating sushi on cell phone during dinner at Ichiban in Berkeley, overheard by Jonathan Moy.)

"You're starting to smell like an older woman, and I'm really loving it.'' (Twenty-ish guy to 20-ish woman, overheard near Caffe Trieste in Berkeley by Gary Handman.)

"I wanted my wedding to be in September so that all three marriages would be in the same month.'' (Overheard at the French Laundry in Yountville by Betty D.)

"We are not in love, ours is a purely textual relationship.'' (Woman on elevator discussing her messaging boyfriend, overheard by Frank Grimaldi.)

COLD HARD FACTS

"They're not men, they're boys. I learned that last year. I'm not making that mistake again.'' (One young woman to another, overheard at Occidental College in Louisiana by John Selawsky.)

"I don't think I am going to change. I am 36.'' (Man to woman, overheard in the Galleria in San Francisco by Donna Schempp.)

"Do you know where the marriage license is? No, it's under 'unimportant documents.''' (Teacher on cell phone to wife, overheard in a faculty room by Sarah Roggero.)

"I've been faking orgasms for a year; the least you can do is fake listening to me.'' (Woman to man, overheard at the Drunken Fish Restaurant in Oakland by Victor Miller.)

"There is no buzz in the second plateau of our relationship.'' (Woman to woman at the craps table at Caesar's Palace in Las Vegas, overheard by Garry Graham.)

"I treat my girlfriend like a bank treats a loan applicant.'' (Man to woman, overheard at Citizen Thai and the Monkey in San Francisco by Ragnar Carlson.)

LIFESTYLE ISSUES

"Well, forget the sex. I'm buying ice cream even if it isn't on sale.'' (Man on cell phone, apparently to his wife, overheard at Long's in San Rafael by Kendra Falconer.)

"How could he not know that pretty girls do not eat dessert? . Then he ate ice cream in front of me. I am so not going out with him ever again.'' (Young woman in financial district office, overheard by co-worker.)

"I can't believe we're going to watch a documentary. What kind of Saturday night is this?'' (Young woman to young woman, overheard at Le Video by Ray Kuryla.)

"He has a very unfortunate turquoise sweater, which I am going to destroy as soon as I get to know him a bit more.'' (Man overheard on Muni by Joe Lee.)

"You give me a headache 24/7.'' (Young man on cell phone, overheard on Battery Street by David Marx.)

EXTRACURRICULAR ACTIVITIES

"You really shouldn't have had sex with your boss in the conference room during lunch.'' "I know. I'm going to try to not do it again.'' (Conversation between a man and a woman, overheard at Delfina by Wynne Brown.)

"I don't know to what point fidelity is healthy.'' (One young American to another, sitting on the steps of a school on Boulevard Raspail in Paris, overheard by Ralph and Zani Weber.)'

"He's got a girlfriend and a wife on the side.'' (Waitress to waitress, upon watching a customer leave Country Way restaurant in Fremont, overheard by Eric Dahl.)

"There's nothing wrong with having an on-line boyfriend and an outside boyfriend.'' (One adolescent girl to another, overheard at Sanchez Library in Pacifica by Stephanie Conrad.)

"I've only cheated once, but I gave him prior notice.'' (Woman to two friends, overheard at Pearl Alley Bistro in Santa Cruz by Ann Davenport.)

"Even nymphomaniacs want a little loyalty.'' (Female tax specialist talking to a client at a professional tax preparation service, overheard by Jerry Kay.)

"When my husband and I got married 25 years ago, we made a pact to have an open marriage and we've stuck to it ever since. But God, I'm so bored with my boyfriend.'' (Woman at the World Horror Convention at the Holiday Inn in San Francisco, overheard by Thomas Burchfield.)

LITTLE THINGS COUNT

"With Tom and me, it was all about the sofa.'' (Woman on cell phone on Sacramento Street, overheard by Fran Johns.)

"Don't put in roses. It might be misinterpreted.'' (Customer at Iris Flower Shop in San Francisco, overheard by Anne Riley.)

"I had a relationship once that was all about commas.'' (A male English major reminisces, overheard by Carolyn Bradley.)

"You know, it's been three years now and I still can't get used to his hair color.'' (Young matron outside the Geary theater, overheard by James Heig.)

"You dated a man who wears bow ties? Don't you know those guys can't face reality?'' (Woman to woman, overheard at Peet's on Montgomery Street by Chris Jehle.)

VOICES OF EXPERIENCE

"It's a good thing you only get married twice.'' (One shopping bag-laden woman to another, overheard at the Corte Madera Village by Joanne Abrams.)

"You really know you are old when your girlfriend is 73.'' (One white-haired gent to another, in line at Trader Joe's in Millbrae, overheard by Patty Bloom.)

"My first marriage only lasted 53 years.'' (Gent overheard at the Washington Square Bar and Grill by Ed Addeo.)

"I would have married someone else, if I hadn't been ovulating.'' (Woman to woman, overheard in the dining area of Ikea in Sacramento by Pati Johnson.)

"No, not that one. The one who got his jaw broken outside the Dubliner Bar, that's her boyfriend.'' (Overheard in Squaw Valley by Bill Smith.)

"And that's how I got crabs the second time.'' (Guy to two women walking along Union Street, overheard by Mike Stine.)

ALONE AGAIN

"So I broke up with him by text message. Is that lame?'' (Twentyish woman on cell phone, overheard at the Powell Street BART station by The Chronicle's Michael Cabanatuan.)

"Her, the bank account and me have parted ways.'' (Man standing in the doorway of an adult sex arcade on Turk Street, overheard by Anna Chan.)

"I'm going to see a show at the Great American Music Hall, then go home and have sex with myself.'' (Man on cell phone in line outside show, overheard by Robert Weiner.)

"I'm in the middle of breaking up with my girlfriend of seven years, but I also subletting my apartment to her twin sister.'' (Man overheard at the flea market in Santa Cruz.)

"I'm getting a dog on Saturday to replace my wife.'' (Man to man, overheard at Starbucks by Shirley Norton.)

"Even though we're still legally married. '' (One woman to another, overheard on Hopkins Street in Berkeley by Alan Meisel, who regrets not hearing what followed.)

"I don't enjoy cigarettes as much, now that I don't have sex.'' (Two men on a Sacramento Street corner, overheard by Mark Murphy.)

"No, I never went out with him. I just slept with him. He was so not my type.'' (Overheard at Golden Gateway post office in Embarcadero One by Catherine Luciano.)

"I'm on a two-week sperm vacation.'' (One young woman to another, overheard at the Montgomery Street BART station by Rozz.)

"I love you, but I just don't need to see you every day.'' (Man on cell phone, overheard in Horizon airlines boarding area in Portland by Holly Pierce.)

THE PEANUT GALLERY

"I was hoping she would break his heart before they got married, not after.'' "Yeah. Now you have to act supportive.'' (Conversation between two women travelers waiting for the 38 Geary, overheard by Nina Guglielmana.)

"The neighbor's husband is the real father.'' (One package service delivery man to another, overheard on Sanchez Street by Sue Olivier.)

"She really HAS to stop marrying gay guys!'' (Overheard by Linda McCausland at Savor on 24th Street.)

"He's an alpha and she's an alpha and I told her two alphas would never get along.'' (Woman to woman, overheard while walking around Lake Merritt by Jean Levin.)

SORE AND SAD

"She dumped me for the Lord.'' (Man at Starbucks near the Tower Market in San Francisco, overheard by Frank Evans.)

"If she gets a harassment order against me, I want one against her sister!'' (Man to man near the Ferry Building, overheard by Jean Abbe.)

"I don't know why he did this. It doesn't make sense.'' "Men don't make sense.'' (Tearful woman in wedding dress commiserates with friend, overheard in Washington Square by Ken Maley.)

"He told me my lack of heart would serve me well in my future divorces.'' (Woman to friends, overheard at the Union Street Fair by David Bourdon.)

"Dude, she was so upset that she called me an intellectual.'' (Punk rocker on cell phone describing his blind date, overheard at Muddy Waters Coffee House in the Mission by David Ryan.)

WHERE THERE'S HOPE

"It's hard to forget about Michelle when I keep finding her hairs in my socks.'' (Young man wistful about his girlfriend or his cat, overheard outside El Cerrito High School by Nora Conners.)

"If I were single, I'd marry you again!'' (Young man on cell phone in Castro, overheard by Michael McKenna.)

"The fact is that I really dumped him, and had forgotten about it.'' (Woman on cell phone, heard in front of Macy's in San Francisco on Valentine's Day by Carol Hill.)
the only thing you actually need is love.
